# Dart and Flutter code quality

Apply these whenever editing Dart in this repo (`name: highlevel` in `pubspec.yaml`).

## Imports (mandatory)

- Use **package imports** for this app and dependencies. Do **not** use relative paths (`../`, `./`) to reach `lib/` or other project files.
- Format: `package:highlevel/<path_under_lib>.dart` (mirror the path under `lib/`).

```dart
// Bad
import '../domain/model/expense.dart';
import './widgets/foo.dart';

// Good
import 'package:highlevel/expense/domain/model/expense.dart';
import 'package:highlevel/expense/presentation/ui/widgets/foo.dart';
```

- `dart:` and `package:` imports only (plus generated part files `part '...g.dart';` where required).

## UI composition (mandatory — no compromise)

- **Do not** use **functions that return `Widget`** to structure UI (e.g. `Widget _buildHeader(...)`, `Widget _tile(Item item)`). No exceptions for “small” helpers — use widget classes.
- **Do** extract UI into **private `StatelessWidget` subclasses** (or private `StatefulWidget` when you need state, lifecycle, or `AnimationController`, etc.) in the same file or a colocated file, named clearly (e.g. `_ExpenseListTile`, `_SummaryCard`).
- Prefer **`const` constructors** on those private widgets when all inputs allow it.
- Rationale: widget classes get stable element identity, work properly with `const`, DevTools, and rebuild boundaries; `Widget`-returning methods do not and are discouraged by the framework team for subtree extraction.

```dart
// Bad — function returning Widget
Widget _buildTitle(String text) => Text(text);

// Good — private StatelessWidget
class _Title extends StatelessWidget {
  const _Title({required this.text});
  final String text;
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) => Text(text);
}
```

## Strings and i18n (mandatory)

- **Do not hardcode** strings that the **end user** sees: titles, labels, `AppBar`/`Tooltip`/`Semantics` text, button and menu labels, placeholder/hint text, empty/error states, dialog and snackbar messages, and user-visible validation or error text.
- **Do** load copy through **i18n** — keys in the project’s translation catalog (Flutter default: **ARB** files + **`flutter gen-l10n`** → use **`AppLocalizations.of(context)`** or an approved project wrapper/extension). Add new keys to ARB and reference them from widgets; do not inline English (or any language) for UI copy.
- **OK to keep literals** for: `debugPrint` / debug-only output, identifiers and enum names not shown in UI, tests, regex and parsing, and **non-user** layers (e.g. internal repository keys) — but anything rendered in the UI must come from i18n.
- When adding user-visible strings, **update every shipped locale** (or add the key to the default ARB and follow the team’s process for other languages).

```dart
// Bad — user-visible literal
ElevatedButton(onPressed: onSave, child: const Text('Save'));

// Good — from generated AppLocalizations (after ARB + gen-l10n)
final l10n = AppLocalizations.of(context)!;
ElevatedButton(onPressed: onSave, child: Text(l10n.saveAction));
```

## Colors and theme

- **Prefer theme tokens** when the color’s meaning is **contextual / semantic** (surfaces, text on surfaces, dividers, primary actions, errors, disabled look): use **`Theme.of(context).colorScheme`**, **`Theme.of(context).textTheme`**, and widget defaults that inherit theme (`AppBar`, `Card`, `ListTile`, material buttons) instead of hardcoded `Color(0xFF…)` or scattered `Colors.*` that duplicate the palette.
- Extend the app theme (`ThemeData`, `ColorScheme.fromSeed`, component themes) when the same role is reused across screens — do not re-specify the same hex in many widgets if it belongs in the theme.
- **Exception (no theme required):** When design or product **explicitly** calls for a **fixed** color (e.g. brand lock-up, chart series, map marker, illustration, one-off marketing asset, WCAG-driven override), use a **`const Color(...)`** / named design token **local to that use** — it does **not** have to be added to `ThemeData` if it is not meant to track light/dark or global palette roles.

```dart
final scheme = Theme.of(context).colorScheme;
// Prefer roles from ColorScheme for typical UI
Text('Hello', style: TextStyle(color: scheme.onSurface));
// Fixed brand/spec color — OK without theme when required
const brandAccent = Color(0xFF00AA66);
```

## Analyzer and lints

- Changes must leave **`dart analyze` with zero issues** (no errors or warnings) for the project.
- Respect `analysis_options.yaml` and `flutter_lints`. Do not silence lints with `// ignore:` unless there is a documented, unavoidable reason in that spot.

## Comments

- Prefer **self-explanatory names** over comments. Remove comments that only restate the code, TODO placeholders without owners, or commented-out dead code.
- Keep comments for **non-obvious rationale**, invariants, or public API contracts where they add real value.

## Additional practices (high impact)

1. **Const:** Use `const` on widgets and constructors whenever values are compile-time constant to reduce rebuild work.
2. **Immutability:** Prefer `final` for locals and fields; use `var` only when reassignment is required.
3. **Build method:** Keep `build` cheap — no async work, I/O, or heavy computation; move that to blocs/use cases/initState/futures.
4. **Async + context:** After `await`, before using `BuildContext`, call `if (!context.mounted) return;` (or equivalent) to avoid using disposed widgets.
5. **Dispose:** Override `dispose` and dispose `TextEditingController`, `AnimationController`, `ScrollController`, `FocusNode`, cancel `StreamSubscription` / timers created by the widget.
6. **Lists:** Prefer `ListView.builder` / `SliverList` (or paginated APIs) for long or unbounded lists instead of building all children eagerly.
7. **Keys:** Use `Key` / `ValueKey` when list order changes, or when Flutter must distinguish sibling widgets of the same type.
8. **Errors:** Do not use empty `catch` blocks; log, handle with typed failures, or rethrow. Align with the project’s error model (e.g. bloc/repo patterns).
9. **Logging:** Avoid `print` in app/library code; use `debugPrint` or the project’s logging approach.
10. **Types:** Prefer explicit types on public APIs and non-obvious members; avoid `dynamic` unless intentionally interoperating with untyped data (then narrow quickly).

When adding code, **run `dart analyze`** (or `flutter analyze`) and fix all reported issues before finishing.
